# Move the end-effector through each waypoint in order (blocking: returns
# once all waypoints are visited, or on first planning/execution failure).
# Poses are in the MoveGroupInterface's planning frame (see TrajectoryPlanner).
geometry_msgs/Pose[] waypoints

# Which MoveIt planning strategy to use for each waypoint-to-waypoint move.
# PLANNING_MODE_CARTESIAN is the default: a straight-line interpolated
# path between waypoints, useful for calibration (predictable geometry)
# but can fail partway (collision/IK/joint-limit) — see TrajectoryPlanner's
# planAndExecuteCartesian(). PLANNING_MODE_JOINT_SPACE is the older,
# more-robust-but-unpredictable-path behavior (MoveGroupInterface::plan(),
# no straight-line guarantee).
uint8 PLANNING_MODE_JOINT_SPACE = 0
uint8 PLANNING_MODE_CARTESIAN = 1
uint8 planning_mode 1

# Optional: name of the destination pose (e.g. "home", "cal_ready",
# "standby", or any preset_poses_*.yaml entry), for ~/current_pose_name
# reporting. Leave empty for arbitrary/unnamed waypoints (e.g. calibration
# polygon corners) — those aren't meaningful to show a human as "the
# current pose". Only applies when waypoints has exactly one pose; ignored
# for multi-waypoint calls.
string pose_name

# Optional: marks this call as a "sequenced goal" — one of the arm's
# regular working stops, as opposed to a special named stop like
# "home"/"cal_ready"/"standoff"/"standby". Only single-waypoint calls with
# this set to true trigger TrajectoryPlanner's wait/return/standby
# behavior (see trajectory_planner.hpp's ArmState doc comment). Default
# false — every existing caller (home, cal_ready, the calibration polygon
# sweep) is unaffected unless it explicitly opts in.
#
# In plain terms: TrajectoryPlanner itself has no idea what a waypoint
# "means" — it just moves to whatever pose it's given. This flag is the
# caller explicitly saying "treat this one as a regular stop, not a
# special one" — the node isn't guessing that from the pose's name or
# position, it's being told outright, the same way planning_mode above
# already tells it which planning strategy to use.
#
# Once set, TrajectoryPlanner tracks a small amount of bookkeeping about
# its OWN recent activity — "did I just execute a move that was flagged as
# a sequenced goal, and if so, what pose was I at right before that move,
# and has enough time passed since." That's it. It's not reasoning about
# the robot's task or intent, just remembering one fact (the previous
# pose) and running two timers off it. The "state" (IDLE/SETTLED_AT_GOAL/
# RETURNING_IDLE/STANDBY, see ArmState) is really just naming those
# bookkeeping phases, not the node understanding anything new about the
# world — trajectory_planner goes from "purely stateless, forgets
# everything the instant a call finishes" to "remembers one previous pose
# and runs a couple of timers", a small, bounded amount of self-awareness,
# not general awareness of "where it is in the overall calibration
# workflow."
bool is_sequenced_goal false
---
bool success
string message